">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span>20.1168&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Metre">m</a></td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>The <b>chain</b> (abbreviated <b>ch</b>) is a <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Units_of_measurement" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Units o=
f measurement">unit</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Length"=
 title=3D"Length">length</a> equal to 66 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Foot_(unit)" title=3D"Foot (unit)">feet</a> (22 <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yard_(unit_of_length)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Yard (unit of length)">yards</a>), used in both the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_customary_units" title=3D"United States cus=
tomary units">US customary</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Imperial_units" title=3D"Imperial units">Imperial</a> unit systems. It is =
subdivided into 100 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Link_(unit)" t=
itle=3D"Link (unit)">links</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-1"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup=
><sup id=3D"cite_ref-USNBS1960_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-USNBS1960-2"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> There =
are 10 chains in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Furlong" title=
=3D"Furlong">furlong</a>, and 80 chains in one <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Statute_mile" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statute mile">sta=
tute mile</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-USNBS1960_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-USNBS1960-2"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> In metric terms, it is 20.1168&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Metre">m</a> long.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-USNBS1960_2-=
2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit=
)#cite_note-USNBS1960-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By extension, <b>chainage</b> (running=
 distance) is the distance along a curved or straight survey line from a fi=
xed commencing point, as given by an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Odometer" title=3D"Odometer">odometer</a>.
</p><p>The chain has been used since the early 17th century in England, and=
 was taken by British settlers during the colonial period to other countrie=
s around the globe. In the United Kingdom, there were 80 chains to the mile=
, but until the early nineteenth century the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Mile#British_and_Irish_miles" title=3D"Mile">Scottish and Irish =
customary miles</a> were longer than the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Statute_mile" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statute mile">statute m=
ile</a>; consequently a Scots chain was about 74 (imperial) feet,<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
hain_(unit)#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> an Irish chain 84 feet. These longer c=
hains became obsolete following the adoption of <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Imperial_units" title=3D"Imperial units">the imperial system =
of units</a> in 1824.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In India=
, "metric chains" of exactly 20 metres (65.62 feet) are used, along with fr=
actions thereof.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Punmia_etal_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-Punmia_etal-5=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChain_(unit)&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The UK statute chain is 22 yards, which is 66 feet (20.1168&nbsp;m). Thi=
s unit is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statute_measure" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Statute measure">statute measure</a> in the Unite=
d Kingdom, defined in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weights_=
and_Measures_Act_1985" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Weights and Measures =
Act 1985">Weights and Measures Act 1985</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1985Act_6-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)=
#cite_note-1985Act-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> One link is a hundredth part of a chain, w=
hich is 7.92 inches (20.1168&nbsp;cm).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Rankine_7-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_=
note-Rankine-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The surveyor's chain first appears in an illustration in a Dutch map=
 of 1607,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-map_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-map-8"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and in an =
English book for surveyors of 1610.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"referenc=
e"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-9"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> In 1593 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile#English_mil=
e" title=3D"Mile">English mile</a> was redefined by a statute of <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Queen_Elizabeth_I" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Queen Elizabeth I">Queen Elizabeth I</a> as 5,280 feet, to tie in wit=
h <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Composition_of_Yards_and_Perches=
" title=3D"Composition of Yards and Perches">agricultural practice</a>. In =
1620, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polymath" title=3D"Polym=
ath">polymath</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edmund_Gunter" t=
itle=3D"Edmund Gunter">Edmund Gunter</a> developed a method of accurately s=
urveying land using a surveyor's chain 66&nbsp;feet long with 100 links.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The 66-foot unit, which was f=
our perches or rods,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Slater&amp;Saunders_11-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-=
Slater&amp;Saunders-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> took on the name the chain. By 1675 it=
 was accepted, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Ogilby" ti=
tle=3D"John Ogilby">Ogilby</a> wrote:
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>...a Word or two of Dimensurators or=
 Measuring Instruments, whereof the most usual has been the Chain, and the =
common length for English Measures 4 Poles, as answering indifferently to t=
he English Mile and Acre, 10 such Chains in length making a Furlong, and 10=
 single square Chains an Acre, so that a square Mile contains 640 square Ac=
res...<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> </p></blockquote><di=
v class=3D"templatequotecite"><p style=3D"display: inline; padding-left: 2.=
3em;">=E2=80=94=E2=80=8AJohn Ogilby, <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Britannia_(atlas)" title=3D"Britannia (atlas)">Britannia</a></i>, 167=
5<span style=3D"display:none" data-plural=3D"0"></span></p></div>
<p>From <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunter%27s_chain" title=3D=
"Gunter's chain">Gunter's system</a>, the chain and the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Link_(unit)" title=3D"Link (unit)">link</a> became st=
andard surveyors' units of length and crossed to the colonies. The thirteen=
 states of America were expanding westward and the public land had to be su=
rveyed for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cadastral" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Cadastral">cadastral</a>. In 1784 <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Jefferson" title=3D"Thomas Jefferson">Thomas Je=
fferson</a> wrote a report for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Continental_Congress" title=3D"Continental Congress">Continental Congress<=
/a> proposing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Land_Ordinance_o=
f_1785#History" title=3D"Land Ordinance of 1785">rectangular survey system<=
/a>; it was adopted with some changes as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Land_Ordinance_of_1785" title=3D"Land Ordinance of 1785">Land Or=
dinance of 1785</a> on 20 May the following year. In the report, the use of=
 the chain as a unit of measurement was mandated, and the chain was defined=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cazier_13-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-Cazier-13"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=20
</p>
 <link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:=
r1244412712"><blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>The chain is the unit o=
f linear measurement for the survey of the public lands as prescribed by la=
w. All returns of measurement in the rectangular system are made in the tru=
e horizontal distance in links, chains, and miles. The only exceptions to t=
his rule are special requirements for measurement in feet in mineral survey=
s and townsite surveys.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Cazier_13-1" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-Cazier-13"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>Linear Measurement
</p>
<dl><dd>1 Chain =3D 100 links or 66 feet</dd>
<dd>1 Mile =3D 80 chains or 5,280 feet</dd></dl>
<p>Area Measurement
</p>
<dl><dd>1 Acre =3D 10 square chains or 43,560 square feet</dd>
<dd>1 square mile =3D 640 acres</dd></dl></blockquote><div class=3D"templat=
equotecite"><p style=3D"display: inline; padding-left: 2.3em;">=E2=80=94=E2=
=80=8ALola Cazier (1976), <i>Surveys and Surveyors of the Public Domain 178=
5-1975</i>, page 15<span style=3D"display:none" data-plural=3D"0"></span></=
p></div>
<p><br>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Modern_use_and_historic_cul=
tural_references">Modern use and historic cultural references</h2><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChain_(unit)&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Modern use and historic cul=
tural references"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">Further info=
rmation: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milestone" title=3D"Miles=
tone">Milestone</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_ref=
erencing" title=3D"Linear referencing">Linear referencing</a></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"United_Kingdom">United King=
dom</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChain_(u=
nit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: United Kingd=
om"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></s=
pan></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Bridge_miles_and_chains.jpg" class=3D"mw-file=
-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/th=
umb/4/43/Bridge_miles_and_chains.jpg/250px-Bridge_miles_and_chains.jpg" dec=
oding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"185" class=3D"mw-file-element" data=
-file-width=3D"1368" data-file-height=3D"1013"></a><figcaption>Location mar=
ker painted on a British railway bridge, showing 112 miles and 63 chains; p=
hotograph taken August 2007</figcaption></figure>
<p>In the United Kingdom, the chain is no longer used for practical survey =
work.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> However, it is still =
used on the railways as a location identifier. When railways were designed,=
 the location of features such as bridges and stations was indicated by a c=
umulative longitudinal "mileage", using miles and chains, from a zero point=
 at the origin or headquarters of the railway, or the originating junction =
of a new branch line. Since railways are linear in topology, the "mileage" =
or "chainage" is sufficient to identify a place uniquely on any given route=
. Thus, a given bridge location may be indicated as 112 miles and 63 chains=
 (181.51&nbsp;km) from the origin. In the case of the photograph, the bridg=
e is near <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Keynsham" title=3D"Keyns=
ham">Keynsham</a>, which is that distance from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/London_Paddington_station" title=3D"London Paddington station"=
>London Paddington station</a>. The indication "MLN" after the mileage is t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineer%27s_Line_Reference" ti=
tle=3D"Engineer's Line Reference">Engineer's Line Reference</a> describing =
the route as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Great_Western_Mai=
n_Line" title=3D"Great Western Main Line">Great Western Main Line</a>, whic=
h is needed to uniquely determine the bridge, as there may be points at 112=
 miles 63 chains on other routes.
</p><p>On new railway lines built in the United Kingdom such as <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/High_Speed_1" title=3D"High Speed 1">High Spe=
ed 1</a>, the position along the alignment is still referred to as "chainag=
e", although the value is now expressed in metres.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#ci=
te_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"North_America">North Americ=
a</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChain_(uni=
t)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: North America"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<p>The use of the chain was mandatory in laying out US townships.<sup id=3D=
"cite_ref-Cazier_13-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-Cazier-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A federal law was pa=
ssed in 1785 (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_Land_Surv=
ey_System" title=3D"Public Land Survey System">Public Land Survey Ordinance=
</a>) that all official government surveys must be done with a Gunter's (su=
rveyor's) chain. Chains and links are commonly encountered in older <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metes_and_bounds" title=3D"Metes and boun=
ds">metes and bounds</a> legal descriptions. Distances on township <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plat" title=3D"Plat">plat</a> maps made b=
y the US General Land Office are shown in chains.
</p><p>Under the US <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Public_Land_Su=
rvey_System" title=3D"Public Land Survey System">Public Land Survey System<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lot_(real_estate)" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Lot (real estate)">parcels of land</a> are often descr=
ibed in terms of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Section_(Unit=
ed_States_land_surveying)" title=3D"Section (United States land surveying)"=
>section</a> (640 acres or 259 hectares), quarter-section (160 acres or 64.=
7 hectares), and quarter-quarter-section (40 acres or 16.19 hectares). Resp=
ectively, these square divisions of land are approximately 80 chains (one m=
ile or 1.6&nbsp;km), 40 chains (half a mile or 800&nbsp;m), and 20 chains (=
a quarter mile or 400&nbsp;m) on a side.
</p><p>The chain is still used in agriculture: measuring wheels with a circ=
umference of 0.1 chain (diameter =E2=89=88 2.1&nbsp;ft or 64&nbsp;cm) are s=
till readily available in Canada and the United States. For a rectangular t=
ract, multiplying the number of turns of a chain wheel for each of two adja=
cent sides and dividing by 1,000 gives the area in acres.
</p><p>In Canada, road allowances were originally 1 chain wide and are now =
20 metres.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The unit was also used in mapping the United States along train rout=
es in the 19th century. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Railroad" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Railroad">Railroads</a> in the United States=
 have long since <sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"white-spac=
e:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Manual_of=
_Style/Dates_and_numbers#Chronological_items" title=3D"Wikipedia:Manual of =
Style/Dates and numbers"><span title=3D"The time period mentioned near this=
 tag is ambiguous. (July 2018)">when?</span></a></i>]</sup> used <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal" title=3D"Decimal">decimal</a> fract=
ions of a mile. Some subways such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/New_York_City_Subway" title=3D"New York City Subway">New York City S=
ubway</a> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington_Metro=
" title=3D"Washington Metro">Washington Metro</a> were designed with and co=
ntinue with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_City_Subway=
_chaining" title=3D"New York City Subway chaining">chaining system</a> usin=
g the 100-foot <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Engineer%27s_chain"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Engineer's chain">engineer's chain</a>.<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-ERA_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-ERA-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the United States, the chain is also used as the measure of the r=
ate of spread of wildfires (chains per hour), both in the predictive <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Fire_Danger_Rating_System" titl=
e=3D"National Fire Danger Rating System">National Fire Danger Rating System=
</a> as well as in after-action reports. The term <i>chain</i> is used by w=
ildland firefighters in day-to-day operations as a unit of distance.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Australia_and_New_Zealand">=
Australia and New Zealand</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DChain_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit=
 section: Australia and New Zealand"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australia" title=3D"Australi=
a">Australia</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_Zealand" =
title=3D"New Zealand">New Zealand</a>, most building lots in the past were =
a quarter of an acre, measuring one chain by two and a half chains, and oth=
er lots would be multiples or fractions of a chain.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sedd=
on1998_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
hain_(unit)#cite_note-Seddon1998-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The street <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frontage" title=3D"Frontage">frontages</a> of man=
y houses in these countries are one chain wide=E2=80=94roads were almost al=
ways 1 chain (20.1&nbsp;m) wide in urban areas,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Seddon19=
98_19-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain=
_(unit)#cite_note-Seddon1998-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> sometimes 1.5 chains (30.2&nbs=
p;m) or 2.5 chains (50.3&nbsp;m). Laneways would be half a chain (10.1&nbsp=
;m). In rural areas the roads were wider, up to 10 chains (201.2&nbsp;m) wh=
ere a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stock_route" title=3D"Stock =
route">stock route</a> was required. 5 chains (100.6&nbsp;m) roads were sur=
veyed as major roads or highways between larger towns, 3 chains (60.4&nbsp;=
m) roads between smaller localities,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-20"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup> and 2 chains (40.2&nbsp;m) roads were local roads in farming comm=
unities. Roads named Three Chain Road etc. persist today.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-21" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(u=
nit)#cite_note-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-22"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up>
</p><p>The "Queen's Chain" is a concept that has long existed in New Zealan=
d, of a strip of public land, usually 20 metres (or one chain in pre-metric=
 measure) wide from the high water mark, that has been set aside for public=
 use along the coast, around many lakes, and along all or part of many rive=
rs.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#c=
ite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> These strips exist in various forms (including roa=
d reserves, esplanade reserves, esplanade strips, marginal strips and reser=
ves of various types) but not as extensively and consistently as is often a=
ssumed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Cricket_pitches">Cricket pi=
tches</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChain_=
(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Cricket pi=
tches"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span>=
</span></div>
<p>The chain also survives as the length of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Cricket_pitch" title=3D"Cricket pitch">cricket pitch</a>, being=
 the distance between the stumps.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-26"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</=
span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Measuring_instruments">Meas=
uring instruments</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DChain_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section=
: Measuring instruments"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Civil engineers and surveyors use various instruments including chains t=
o measure distance.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Punmia_etal_5-1" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-Punmia_eta=
l-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Other instruments used for measuring distance include tapes=
 and bands. A steel band is also known as a "band chain".<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(u=
nit)#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Surveyors'_chain_(Gunter's_=
chain)"><span id=3D"Surveyors.27_chain_.28Gunter.27s_chain.29"></span>Surve=
yors' chain (Gunter's chain)</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DChain_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"E=
dit section: Surveyors' chain (Gunter's chain)"><span>edit</span></a><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunter%27s_chain" ti=
tle=3D"Gunter's chain">Gunter's chain</a></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Gunter's_chain"></span>=20
In 1620, the polymath <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edmund_Gunte=
r" title=3D"Edmund Gunter">Edmund Gunter</a> developed a method of accurate=
ly surveying land using a 100 link chain, 22 yards (66 feet) long, called t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunter%27s_Chain" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Gunter's Chain">Gunter's Chain</a>. <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gunter%27s_chain#Similar_measuring_chains" title=3D"Gun=
ter's chain">Other surveyors chains</a> have been used historically.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Engineer's_chain_(Ramsden's=
_chain)"><span id=3D"Engineer.27s_chain_.28Ramsden.27s_chain.29"></span>Eng=
ineer's chain (Ramsden's chain)</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DChain_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D9" title=
=3D"Edit section: Engineer's chain (Ramsden's chain)"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Ramsden's_chain_(engineer's_chain)"></span>
</p>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramsden_surveying_in=
struments#Chains_and_rods" title=3D"Ramsden surveying instruments">Ramsden =
surveying instruments =C2=A7&nbsp;Chains and rods</a></div>
<p>A longer chain of 100 feet (30.5&nbsp;m), with a hundred 1 foot (305&nbs=
p;mm) links, was devised in the UK in the late 18th century by <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ramsden_surveying_instruments" title=3D"Ramsde=
n surveying instruments">Jesse Ramsden</a>, though it never supplanted Gunt=
er's chain.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Rankine_7-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-Rankine-7"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
Surveyors also sometimes used such a device, and called it the <i>engineer'=
s chain</i>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Vara_or_Texas_chain"><span =
title=3D"Spanish-language text"><i lang=3D"es">Vara</i></span> or Texas cha=
in</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChain_(un=
it)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D10" title=3D"Edit section: Vara or Texa=
s chain"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Southwestern_United_Stat=
es" title=3D"Southwestern United States">Southwestern United States</a>, th=
e <i><span title=3D"Spanish-language text"><i lang=3D"es">vara</i></span> c=
hain</i> also called the <i>Texas chain</i>, of 20 <span title=3D"Spanish-l=
anguage text"><i lang=3D"es"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spani=
sh_customary_units#Vara_(unit_of_length)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sp=
anish customary units">varas</a></i></span> (16.9164&nbsp;m (55.5&nbsp;ft))=
 was used in surveying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viceroyalty=
_of_New_Spain" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Viceroyalty of New Spain">Spa=
nish</a> and later <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/First_Mexican_R=
epublic" title=3D"First Mexican Republic">Mexican</a> land grants, such as =
the major <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fisher%E2%80%93Miller_La=
nd_Grant" title=3D"Fisher=E2=80=93Miller Land Grant">Fisher=E2=80=93Miller<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paisano_Grant" title=3D"Pa=
isano Grant">Paisano Grants</a> in Texas, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Land_grants_in_New_Mexico" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Land gran=
ts in New Mexico">several similarly large ones in New Mexico</a>, and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ranchos_of_California" title=3D"Ranchos=
 of California">over 200 smaller <span title=3D"Spanish-language text"><i l=
ang=3D"es">ranchos</i></span> in California</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Metric_chains">Metric chain=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChain_(uni=
t)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D11" title=3D"Edit section: Metric chains=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>Metric chains, of lengths 5&nbsp;m, 10&nbsp;m, 20&nbsp;m and 30&nbsp;m, =
are widely used in India.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Punmia_etal_5-2" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-Punm=
ia_etal-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> Tolerances are =C2=B13&nbsp;mm for 5&nbsp;m and 10&nb=
sp;m chains, =C2=B15&nbsp;mm for a 20&nbsp;m chain, and =C2=B18&nbsp;mm for=
 a 30&nbsp;m chain.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(unit)#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>29<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Revenue_chain">Revenue chai=
n</h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DChain_(uni=
t)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Revenue chain=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>In India, a revenue chain with 16 links and of length 10&nbsp;m (33&nbsp=
;ft) is used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cadastral_surveyin=
g" title=3D"Cadastral surveying">cadastral surveys</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chain_(uni=
t)#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Other_instruments">Other in=
struments</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCh=
ain_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D13" title=3D"Edit section: Other=
 instruments"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>Also in North America, a variant of the chain is used in <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forestry" title=3D"Forestry">forestry</a> for <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Traverse_(surveying)" title=3D"Traver=
se (surveying)">traverse surveys</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template =
Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation neede=
d"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources. (July 20=
18)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> This modern chain is a static co=
rd (thin rope) 50 metres long, marked with a small tag at each metre, and a=
lso marked in the first metre every <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Decimetre" title=3D"Decimetre">decimetre</a>.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline=
-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title=3D"Wikipedia:Cita=
tion needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs references to reliable sources=
. (July 2018)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup> When working in dense =
bush, a short <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Axe#Axes_designed_to=
_cut_or_shape_wood" title=3D"Axe">axe</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Hatchet" title=3D"Hatchet">hatchet</a> is commonly tied to the e=
nd of the chain, and thrown through the bush in the direction of the traver=
se.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em; white=
-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Plea=
se_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"What is it ca=
lled? (July 2018)">clarification needed</span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>Another version used extensively in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Forestry" title=3D"Forestry">forestry</a> and <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surveying" title=3D"Surveying">surveying</a> is the <i=
>hip-chain</i>: a small box containing a string counter, worn on the hip.<s=
up class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:now=
rap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_neede=
d" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs refe=
rences to reliable sources. (July 2018)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</s=
up> The user ties off the spooled string to a stake or tree and the counter=
 tallies distance as the user walks away in a straight line. These instrume=
nts are available in both <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Foot_(un=
it)" title=3D"Foot (unit)">feet</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Metre" title=3D"Metre">metres</a>.
</p>
